# MailBOX Zero — appliance environment template
# Copy to .env and fill in real values before `docker compose up -d`.
#
# This file is the single source of truth for per-appliance config. The
# step-by-step bring-up that consumes it is docs/runbook/customer-onboarding.v0.1.0.md
# (which value to set, in what order, and how to verify each one).
#
# ── How this file is organized (MBOX-182 audit, 2026-05-22) ─────────────
#   1. SECRETS              — never commit a real value; rotate on leak.
#   2. CUSTOMER-SPECIFIC    — must be set per appliance; identifies/binds the box.
#   3. FLEET DEFAULTS       — same on every box; change only for a reason.
#   4. PROVISIONER-ONLY     — read by scripts on the workstation, NOT by the
#                             appliance stack. Lives here for convenience.
#   5. OPTIONAL OVERRIDES   — commented out; uncomment to tune.
#
# IMPORTANT — env plumbing (audit finding, MBOX-182): the dashboard container
# only sees the keys that docker-compose.yml lists under the
# `mailbox-dashboard` service `environment:` block. There is no dotenv loader
# in the dashboard runtime — a var in this file that compose does NOT forward
# is a SILENT NO-OP inside the container. MBOX-306 forwarded the previously
# flagged cloud-drafting and RAG vars, so every var documented below is now
# plumbed through compose. If you add a NEW var that the dashboard reads via
# process.env, you must ALSO add it to the dashboard `environment:` block in
# docker-compose.yml or it will be a silent no-op. See
# docs/runbook/customer-onboarding.v0.1.0.md "Audit findings".

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 1. SECRETS  (never commit a real value)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── Postgres (operational datastore) ────────────────────────────────────
POSTGRES_USER=mailbox
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=changeme_postgres_password   # REQUIRED — secret
POSTGRES_DB=mailbox

# ── n8n credential-store encryption key ─────────────────────────────────
# Encrypts n8n's stored credentials (incl. the Gmail OAuth refresh token).
# Treat as a secret. Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32
# Losing/rotating this orphans every stored n8n credential — you'd re-do
# the Gmail OAuth flow. Back it up alongside POSTGRES_PASSWORD in 1Password.
N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY=changeme_n8n_encryption_key   # REQUIRED — secret

# ── Caddy basic_auth (STAQPRO-131) ──────────────────────────────────────
# Gates /dashboard/* and the n8n editor at root behind a single password.
# Generate a bcrypt hash NON-interactively with:
#   docker run --rm caddy:2 caddy hash-password --plaintext 'YOUR-PASSWORD'
# (the --plaintext flag is REQUIRED without a TTY; piping echo returns empty.)
#
# *** $$ ESCAPING (this bit us on the first Caddy deploy) ***
# bcrypt hashes contain literal `$`. Docker Compose treats `$` as variable
# expansion and SILENTLY TRUNCATES the value at the first `$`, leaving the
# hash empty inside the container. Escape EVERY `$` to `$$` in this file:
#   hash $2a$14$abc...  →  MAILBOX_BASIC_AUTH_HASH=$$2a$$14$$abc...
# Verify after `docker compose up -d caddy` (NOT `restart` — restart reuses
# the baked-in env):  docker exec mailbox-caddy-1 sh -c 'echo ${MAILBOX_BASIC_AUTH_HASH:0:10}'
# Rotation is automated by bin/rotate-basic-auth (handles both footguns).
# Empty hash = Caddy blocks the proxy unauthenticated — DO NOT ship a
# customer appliance with this empty.
MAILBOX_BASIC_AUTH_HASH=                          # REQUIRED — secret ($$-escaped)

# ── Cloudflare API token (DNS-01 cert issuance) ─────────────────────────
# Scope: Zone → DNS → Edit on the chosen zone ONLY (NEVER account-wide — a
# leaked appliance token must blast-radius to exactly one zone).
# Used by:
#   1. Caddy at runtime for DNS-01 cert solving + renewal (Caddyfile reads
#      {env.CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN}).
#   2. scripts/provision-customer-dns.sh on the PROVISIONER WORKSTATION to
#      create the per-customer A record before first boot (STAQPRO-183).
# Same token, same scope serves both. Share via 1Password / out-of-band.
CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=changeme_cloudflare_dns_edit_token   # REQUIRED for public TLS — secret

# ── Ollama Cloud key (cloud-escalation drafting target) ─────────────────
# Same /api/chat surface as the local Ollama daemon. Used when classify
# routes a message to the cloud (escalate / unknown / confidence < 0.75).
# Allocate from the pooled UMB Ollama Cloud account; get a key at
# https://ollama.com/cloud. Empty key = cloud route 401s (local-only box).
# This var IS forwarded to the dashboard container (compose environment:).
OLLAMA_CLOUD_API_KEY=                             # REQUIRED for cloud route — secret

# ── Anthropic key (alt-cloud fallback for drafting; not the default) ────
# The live cloud path is Ollama Cloud (above) per the 2026-04-30 pivot
# superseding DR-23. Anthropic Haiku 4.5 is config-ready alt-cloud — flip
# by populating this key and pointing the draft route at the Anthropic
# provider. Forwarded to the dashboard container (compose environment:).
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-key-here          # OPTIONAL — secret

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 2. CUSTOMER-SPECIFIC  (set per appliance — identifies/binds the box)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── Public hostname (the site address Caddy serves) ─────────────────────
# Substituted into the Caddyfile via {$DOMAIN}. Without this, Caddy crashes
# with an empty site address (STAQPRO-237). Two flavors:
#   1. Customer-owned domain (M1 / Heron Labs): mailbox.heronlabsinc.com
#   2. Shared Staqs subdomain (NC-25, customers 2+, STAQPRO-183):
#        <customer-slug>.mailbox.<MAILBOX_SHARED_DOMAIN>  (e.g. acme.mailbox.staqs.io)
# The A record is created by scripts/provision-customer-dns.sh before first
# boot and points at the appliance's LAN IP; Caddy solves the cert via DNS-01.
DOMAIN=mailbox.example.com                        # REQUIRED — your appliance hostname

# ── Caddy basic_auth username ───────────────────────────────────────────
# Pairs with MAILBOX_BASIC_AUTH_HASH (secrets section). Username is not a
# secret; the hash is. Defaults to admin.
MAILBOX_BASIC_AUTH_USER=admin

# ── Let's Encrypt account email (cert expiry warnings) ──────────────────
# Substituted into the Caddyfile global block via {$CADDY_EMAIL}. If empty,
# certs still issue but you get no expiry warnings.
CADDY_EMAIL=ops@example.com                       # REQUIRED for expiry warnings

# ── Operator email (RAG H2 voice-priming; STAQPRO-221) ──────────────────
# The connected mailbox's own address. When set, retrieval runs TWO Qdrant
# queries in parallel: outbound (from MAILBOX_OPERATOR_EMAIL to the sender —
# "how do we write to them") and inbound (sender — "what have they said").
# Unset = inbound-only retrieval + a once-per-30-min warning. Single-tenant
# only. This var IS forwarded to the dashboard container.
MAILBOX_OPERATOR_EMAIL=                           # RECOMMENDED — connected mailbox address

# ── Operator threshold-alert email (MBOX-185 / FR-22) ───────────────────
# The MailBOX-AlertCheck workflow polls the dashboard alert-check route and,
# when an alarm-severity health condition is firing (and not yet emailed
# today), sends the operator an alert email via appliance Gmail OAuth — the
# same send path + send-from flag convention as the MBOX-132 daily digest
# (DIGEST_SEND_FROM_GMAIL). Recipient resolves to MAILBOX_OPERATOR_EMAIL.
#
# ALERT_SEND_FROM_GMAIL — appliance-OAuth send toggle. Treated as ON unless
# explicitly '0'/'false' (the workflow is imported deliberately, so unset ===
# intended-on, mirroring DIGEST_SEND_FROM_GMAIL). Set '0' to disable the email
# push while leaving the /status alerts intact.
# ALERT_CHECK_INTERVAL_MIN — how often (minutes) MailBOX-AlertCheck polls the
# alert-check route. Forward-or-no-op: unset → 15 (the workflow's own `?? 15`).
# ALERT_SEND_FROM_GMAIL=1
# ALERT_CHECK_INTERVAL_MIN=15

# ── Ollama image (PIN BY DIGEST — STAQPRO-240) ──────────────────────────
# Pin to a specific sha256 digest, NEVER a moving tag. Upstream
# `ollama/ollama:latest` silently bumped M2 0.20.5 → 0.23.0 and triggered a
# Qwen3 thinking-mode classification regression (n8n `think: false` guards
# the symptom but is not a substitute for pinning the runtime).
# Capture the live digest on a healthy appliance you're cloning from:
#   IID=$(docker inspect mailbox-ollama-1 --format '{{.Image}}')
#   docker inspect "$IID" --format '{{range .RepoDigests}}{{.}}{{println}}{{end}}'
# Known-good baselines (2026-05-07):
#   M1: ollama/ollama@sha256:662109db8037f17257cfc6e816289c0d4c9ae8a2a4ff760b653d8d410e234ba0  (0.20.5)
#   M2: ollama/ollama@sha256:5600a652d1081050f398152127c584222546354491f27fe47ccbc6351bc870bd  (0.23.0)
OLLAMA_IMAGE=ollama/ollama@sha256:5600a652d1081050f398152127c584222546354491f27fe47ccbc6351bc870bd

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 3. FLEET DEFAULTS  (same on every box — change only for a reason)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── LAN-side hostname for mDNS discovery (STAQPRO-410) ──────────────────
# Caddy serves this over its internal CA so a customer on the same LAN can
# reach the dashboard at https://mailbox.local/ during first-boot onboarding
# without knowing the appliance IP.
# v1 (now): static `mailbox.local`. Two appliances on one LAN will collide —
#   the runbook documents the DHCP-table fallback.
# v2 (after STAQPRO-409 slug-stamping): set to `<customer-slug>.local`.
MAILBOX_LAN_HOSTNAME=mailbox.local

# ── Local inference runtime selector (STAQPRO-338 / DR-25) ──────────────
# AUDIT FINDING (MBOX-182): these three are interpolated by docker-compose.yml
# (with the defaults shown) and ARE forwarded to the dashboard container, but
# were undocumented in this file until now. Defaults preserve Ollama behavior
# on appliances that don't set them; M1 is on the llama.cpp drafting cutover
# (DR-25 ACCEPTED 2026-05-15). Leave at defaults unless cutting over a box.
#   ollama    = local drafts via the Ollama daemon (legacy default)
#   llama-cpp = local drafts via the llama-cpp server (DR-25 path)
LOCAL_INFERENCE_RUNTIME=ollama
LLAMA_CPP_BASE_URL=http://llama-cpp:8080
LLAMA_CPP_MODEL=qwen3-4b-instruct-2507

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 4. PROVISIONER-ONLY  (read by scripts on the WORKSTATION, not the appliance)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# These are consumed by scripts/provision-customer-dns.sh when creating the
# per-customer Cloudflare A record. They are NOT read by docker-compose or
# any appliance service. Set them in the .env on the provisioner workstation;
# they may be left blank in the appliance's own .env.

# Cloudflare zone ID of the Staqs-owned shared subdomain root (the zone
# covering MAILBOX_SHARED_DOMAIN). Find at: CF dashboard → Zone overview →
# right sidebar "Zone ID". Leave blank on customer-owned-domain appliances
# (e.g. M1 heronlabsinc.com) — those don't go through the shared provisioner.
CLOUDFLARE_ZONE_ID=                               # provisioner-only

# Staqs-owned shared subdomain root for customers 2+ (NC-25). Per-customer
# hostnames are <customer-slug>.mailbox.<MAILBOX_SHARED_DOMAIN>. Customer #1
# (Heron Labs) sits on mailbox.heronlabsinc.com and ignores this var.
# MAILBOX_SHARED_DOMAIN=staqs.io                  # provisioner-only

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 5. OPTIONAL OVERRIDES  (commented out by default)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── Cloud drafting overrides (Ollama Cloud) ─────────────────────────────
# MBOX-306: now forwarded to the dashboard container (docker-compose.yml
# mailbox-dashboard `environment:` block). The dashboard reads these via
# process.env in lib/drafting/router.ts:39-40. Values below are the code
# defaults — uncomment and change to override the cloud base URL or model.
# OLLAMA_CLOUD_BASE_URL=https://ollama.com
# OLLAMA_CLOUD_MODEL=gpt-oss:120b

# ── Local-model A/B knob (MAILBOX_LOCAL_MODEL_OVERRIDE) ─────────────────
# Swaps the local-route draft model in lib/drafting/router.ts pickEndpoint().
# Cloud route is unaffected. IS forwarded to the dashboard container.
# Pre-flight: pull the model on the appliance first
#   ssh mailbox2 'docker exec mailbox-ollama-1 ollama pull qwen3.5:4b'
# A missing tag 404s every local draft until the var is reverted.
# Rollback: remove the line and `docker compose up -d mailbox-dashboard`
# (NOT `restart` — see root CLAUDE.md ".env rotation gotchas").
# MAILBOX_LOCAL_MODEL_OVERRIDE=qwen3.5:4b-ctx4k

# ── Constrained decoding (GBNF) — MBOX-120 SPIKE, default OFF ────────────
# Enforces a structure-only GBNF grammar on reorder + scheduling local drafts
# (llama.cpp runtime only; Ollama ignores it). Default OFF — constrained
# decoding risks semantic degradation, so this stays a flagged spike until
# grammar-eval.ts + a human blind-pref pass clear it. Set to 1/true to enable.
CONSTRAINED_DECODING_ENABLED=0

# ── RAG retrieval tunables (STAQPRO-191 / 221 / 222) ────────────────────
# MBOX-306: now forwarded to the dashboard container (docker-compose.yml
# mailbox-dashboard `environment:` block). The dashboard reads these via
# process.env in lib/rag/retrieve.ts:154-200. Values below are the code
# defaults — uncomment and change to tune.
#
# RAG_CLOUD_ROUTE_ENABLED is the cloud-route privacy gate (default off per
# root CLAUDE.md "RAG retrieval → Privacy gate"). Set to 1 to allow retrieved
# corpus snippets to feed cloud-route prompts; leave unset/off to keep
# cloud-route drafts on the persona-stub fallback. Now plumbed through compose,
# so RAG_CLOUD_ROUTE_ENABLED=1 here actually enables it.
# RAG_CLOUD_ROUTE_ENABLED=1
#
# MAILBOX_REDRAFT_ENABLED (P3 / MBOX-162) — operator redraft-with-prompt loop.
# Default off: the /api/internal/draft-redraft endpoint 403s and the queue hides
# the "Redraft with prompt" button until this is 1. Local-only (DR-53). Plumbed
# through compose, so MAILBOX_REDRAFT_ENABLED=1 here actually enables it. Recreate
# the dashboard after changing (docker compose up -d --force-recreate mailbox-dashboard).
# MAILBOX_REDRAFT_ENABLED=1
# RAG_RETRIEVE_TOP_K=3
# RAG_RETRIEVE_TOP_K_OUTBOUND=2
# RAG_RETRIEVE_TOP_K_INBOUND=1
# RAG_MIN_INBOUND_CHARS=40
# RAG_MIN_SCORE=0.70
# RAG_RETRIEVE_EXCLUDE_SAME_THREAD=1

# ── Appliance git-state visibility (MBOX-163) ───────────────────────────
# The dashboard surfaces live appliance git state (branch / short_sha /
# commits_behind_master / fetch_age / dirty) on /api/system/status via a
# READ-ONLY host repo bind mount. Closes the STAQPRO-336 incident class:
# M1 sat on worktree-staqpro-360 at 198e105 for 36h with local master
# 19 commits behind origin, invisible from off-the-box; Eric burned a
# rebuild before noticing.
#
# HOST_REPO_DIR is the path on the HOST that holds the repo. Default
# /home/bob/mailbox matches the M1 layout (root CLAUDE.md → Deploy flow).
# Override per-appliance if you clone the repo elsewhere.
# HOST_REPO_DIR=/home/bob/mailbox
#
# MAILBOX_REPO_MOUNT is the path the dashboard CONTAINER reads (i.e. the
# bind mount's TARGET). Default /app/repo matches docker-compose.yml.
# Only override if you remount the repo somewhere else in the container.
# MAILBOX_REPO_MOUNT=/app/repo
#
# Cross-session deploy check (no SSH needed):
#   curl -su admin:$PW https://mailbox.heronlabsinc.com/dashboard/api/system/status \
#     | jq .git_state

# ── Swap + orphan-container visibility (MBOX-168) ───────────────────────
# Companion stats to memory_pressure, surfacing two failure classes that
# burned ~4 agent runs on the DR-25 misdiagnosis (the actual cause was a
# 3.86 GiB orphan llama-cpp container hoarding RAM):
#   swap_in_use       — /proc/meminfo SwapTotal-SwapFree (green/yellow/red)
#   orphan_containers — running on host but NOT in docker-compose.yml
# Orphan detection requires the /var/run/docker.sock bind on mailbox-dashboard
# (already in docker-compose.yml). See CLAUDE.md "Swap + orphan containers".
#
# MAILBOX_SWAP_THRESHOLD_MIB — yellow→red threshold for swap-in-use (MiB).
# 0..threshold = yellow (zram noise floor). Default 100 MiB.
# MAILBOX_SWAP_THRESHOLD_MIB=100
#
# COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME — used to build expected container-name pattern
# `<project>-<svc>-1`. Defaults to "mailbox" matching docker-compose's default
# (directory name). Override only if you deploy under a non-default project.
# COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME=mailbox

# ── OTA image pinning (MBOX-184) ────────────────────────────────────────
# The two locally-built services (mailbox-dashboard + caddy) are published to
# GHCR by .github/workflows/publish-images.yml on push-to-master / tag. GHCR is
# the authoritative store of the latest published digest — the /status panel
# reads it live from the registry (MBOX-347), no committed manifest file.
#
# docker-compose.yml references each via `image: ${DASHBOARD_IMAGE:-mailbox-dashboard:local}`
# (and CADDY_IMAGE). The design is NON-BREAKING for M1:
#   - UNSET (default): `image:` resolves to the local tag, and M1's existing
#     `docker compose up -d --build` keeps rebuilding + tagging locally as
#     before. Nothing changes on the current appliance.
#   - SET to a GHCR digest-pinned ref: a plain `docker compose up -d` (NO
#     --build) pulls that exact digest. This is the OTA / clean-install path.
#
# Pin to the latest published registry digest — read it straight from GHCR:
#   docker buildx imagetools inspect ghcr.io/umb-advisors/mailbox-dashboard:latest
#   docker buildx imagetools inspect ghcr.io/umb-advisors/mailbox-caddy:latest
# (use the index/manifest-list digest the panel compares against), then:
#   DASHBOARD_IMAGE=ghcr.io/umb-advisors/mailbox-dashboard@sha256:<digest>
#   CADDY_IMAGE=ghcr.io/umb-advisors/mailbox-caddy@sha256:<digest>
# The dashboard's read-only "OTA updates" /status panel compares the live GHCR
# digests against the running container digests. The "Update now" apply path is
# a deferred MBOX-184 follow-up; for now apply updates from the shell.
# DASHBOARD_IMAGE=ghcr.io/umb-advisors/mailbox-dashboard@sha256:CHANGEME
# CADDY_IMAGE=ghcr.io/umb-advisors/mailbox-caddy@sha256:CHANGEME

# ── Gmail credentials ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# NOT an env var. Provisioned via the n8n Gmail OAuth flow on the appliance;
# the refresh token lives in n8n's encrypted credential store (Postgres +
# N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY). See docs/runbook/customer-onboarding.v0.1.0.md step 3.
#
# IMAP/SMTP fallback below is NOT the active path (DR-22 settled on Gmail
# Get + Gmail Reply n8n nodes via OAuth). Left here for emergency reference;
# these keys are read by nothing in the live stack.
# IMAP_HOST=imap.gmail.com
# IMAP_USER=operator@example.com
# IMAP_PASSWORD=changeme_imap_app_specific_password
# SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
# SMTP_USER=operator@example.com
# SMTP_PASSWORD=changeme_smtp_app_specific_password

# ── GitHub Packages auth (MBOX-325) ───────────────────────────────────────
# Required to install @umb-advisors/* packages (currently @umb-advisors/llm)
# from GitHub Packages npm registry during the dashboard container build.
# Scope: read:packages (and write:packages only if you publish from here —
# the dashboard build only needs read).
#
# Set via:
#   - operator workstation: `export GITHUB_PACKAGES_TOKEN=$(gh auth token)`
#     after `gh auth refresh -s read:packages`, OR a classic PAT
#   - appliance .env: paste a PAT here
# Used by:
#   1. docker-compose `mailbox-dashboard.build.args` (passes through to
#      Dockerfile ARG, expands dashboard/.npmrc at install time)
#   2. local `npm install` in dashboard/ via dashboard/.npmrc
GITHUB_PACKAGES_TOKEN=changeme_github_pat_with_read_packages   # REQUIRED for dashboard build — secret

# ── Dashboard Google OAuth (MBOX-398 / MBOX-130 / MBOX-129) ────────────────
# Powers the right-rail Calendar / Contacts / Tasks panels, the scheduling
# calendar pre-read, and the push-to-Tasks handoff. ALL OPTIONAL — leave unset
# and the dashboard runs fine; the Integrations "Connect" buttons just return
# "GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID / GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET not set" instead of
# redirecting to Google.
#
# To enable:
#   1. In a Google Cloud project (you can reuse the one backing the n8n Gmail
#      OAuth client), enable the Calendar, Tasks, and People APIs.
#   2. Create an OAuth 2.0 Client ID, type "Web application".
#   3. Add this Authorized redirect URI (exact):
#        https://<your-host>/dashboard/api/oauth/google/callback
#      e.g. https://mailbox.heronlabsinc.com/dashboard/api/oauth/google/callback
#   4. If the OAuth consent screen is in "Testing", add the operator's Google
#      account as a test user.
#   5. Paste the client id/secret below, generate the two secrets, set the base
#      URL, then `docker compose up -d mailbox-dashboard` (NOT restart).
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=                       # from the Google OAuth 2.0 Web client
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=                   # secret
# 32-byte hex each (`openssl rand -hex 32`). TOKEN_KEY encrypts refresh tokens
# at rest (AES-256-GCM); STATE_SECRET signs the connect-flow state HMAC. Keep
# them DISTINCT (key separation). Losing TOKEN_KEY orphans stored tokens →
# operator must reconnect each provider.
MAILBOX_OAUTH_TOKEN_KEY=                      # secret
MAILBOX_OAUTH_STATE_SECRET=                   # secret
# Public https origin of THIS appliance — builds the OAuth callback URL.
MAILBOX_PUBLIC_BASE_URL=https://mailbox.heronlabsinc.com
# Dashboard basePath; default /dashboard (matches Caddy + the build). Only
# change if you serve the dashboard at a different path.
NEXT_PUBLIC_BASE_PATH=/dashboard
